Airline On-Time Performance Analysis (Part I)¶

Exploratory Visualizations¶

by Judith Agara¶

Introduction¶

Dataset Description: This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays in the year 2006. It also contains data on airports and airplanes. Four (4) tables/.csv files are used in this analysis. They include:

  1. 2006.csv - flights report in the year 2006
  2. carriers.csv - airline information
  3. airports.csv - airport information such as city, state, country, latitude and longitude.
  4. plane-data.csv - plane info such as type, manufacturer, model, engine type, etc.

All files are available for download here

Quality Issues¶

  • capitalized letters in column names in the flights table (for uniformity, all column names should be lowercase and words should be sepearated using underscores)
  • some arrival and departure times have only 1 or 2 digits that seem not to correspond to a valid time. This is probably because excel removes leading 0s and we can have up to about 3 leading 0s (add the missing leading 0s).
  • incorrect time representation - (change the arrival and departure times to hh:mm format by inserting ":" at appropriate points)
  • Year, Month, DayofMonth and DayofWeek columns (use the year, month and day of month to form a date column), (change month from numbers 1-12 to Jan-Dec), (change day of week from 1-7 to Mon-Sun and make them categorical types), (year should also be changed to str dtype), (day of month should be string)
  • the cancellation code in the flights table should be transformed as follows: (reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security)
  • the cancelled column should be transformed as follows: (0 = NO, 1 = YES)
  • the missing values in the CancellationCode column - (if flight was not cancelled, let reason be 'not cancelled')
  • missing arrival and departure times in flights table, missing departure times corresponds to cancelled flight - (but some records have departure times but missing arrival times and these flights were not cancelled, these rows should be dropped)
  • duplicates in flights table - (drop duplicates)
  • one missing airline code in the airlines table - (drop this)
  • rename year column in airplanes table to manufacturing_year
  • rename Description column in airplanes table to airline
  • incorrect datatype (the issue_date in the airplanes table should be datetime), (latitude and longitude in the airports table should be str datatypes)
  • extract year from issue_date to replace the year column as it has some incorrect entries
  • 12 records missing city and state values in the airports table - (these can be found using the geopy module and by an online search using the airport name, find and input these values)
  • 549 records only have 'tailnum' recorded in the airplanes table - (these will not be relevant to the analysis, they should be dropped)

After these cleaning operations, I will recompute the ArrDelay and DepDelay columns.

Tidiness Issues¶

  • drop columns that are not needed
  • merge the resulting flights table with the airports, airplanes and airlines table to form one master dataset which will be explored further using exploratory visualizations.

Finally, the last step will be to engineer a flight status column that identifies a flight as "on-time" or "delayed".

  • A flight is considered on-time when it arrives less than 15 minutes after its published arrival time. A flight arriving or departing 15 minutes or more after the scheduled time is considered a late flight.

column_names = ['year', 'month', 'day', 'day_of_week', 'dep_time', 'sched_dep_time', 'arr_time', 'sched_arr_time',
                'carrier_code', 'flight_num', 'tailnum', 'arr_delay', 'dep_delay', 'iata_origin', 'iata_dest', 'distance',
                'cancelled', 'reason_for_cancel']

months_dict = {1:'Jan', 2:'Feb', 3:'Mar', 4:'Apr', 5:'May', 6:'Jun', 7:'Jul', 8:'Aug', 9:'Sept', 10:'Oct', 11:'Nov', 12:'Dec'}

day_of_week_dict = {1:'Mon', 2:'Tues', 3:'Wed', 4:'Thurs', 5:'Fri', 6:'Sat', 7:'Sun'}

cancel_reason_dict = {'A':'carrier', 'B':'weather', 'C':'NAS', 'D':'security', np.nan:'not cancelled'}

cancelled = {0:'NO', 1:'YES'}
In [26]:
def clean_flight_record(df):
    """
        Function to perform cleaning operations on flight record tables. This cleaning operations address the
        quality issues detected and documented above.
        
        Input: flight record dataframe to be cleaned (clean_05 or clean_06).
        
        Returns: a cleaned dataframe
    """
    # subset table to drop records with departure time but no arrival time
    df = df[~(df['DepTime'].notnull() & df['ArrTime'].isnull())]
    
    # fill missing departure and arrival times with 0s
    df['DepTime'].fillna(0, inplace=True)
    df['ArrTime'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

    # change column names
    df.columns = column_names

    # change encoding for month and day_of_week, cancel and cancel code
    df['month'].replace(months_dict, inplace=True)
    df['day_of_week'].replace(day_of_week_dict, inplace=True)
    df['cancelled'].replace(cancelled, inplace=True)
    df['reason_for_cancel'].replace(cancel_reason_dict, inplace=True)

    # drop duplicate records
    df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True, ignore_index=True)

    # setting appropriate datatypes
    df['year'] = df['year'].astype(str)
    df['day'] = df['day'].astype(str)
    months = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul',
                                                                         'Aug', 'Sept', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
    weekday = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ['Mon', 'Tues', 'Wed', 'Thurs', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun'])   
    df['month'] = df['month'].astype(months)
    df['day_of_week'] = df['day_of_week'].astype(weekday)
    df['dep_time'] = df['dep_time'].astype(int) # change from float to int first to remove the floating point
    df['dep_time'] = df['dep_time'].astype(str)
    df['sched_dep_time'] = df['sched_dep_time'].astype(str)
    df['arr_time'] = df['arr_time'].astype(int) # change from float to int first to remove the floating point
    df['arr_time'] = df['arr_time'].astype(str)
    df['sched_arr_time'] = df['sched_arr_time'].astype(str)
    
    
    # format time to 4-digit strings
    df['dep_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: '000'+x['dep_time'] if len(x['dep_time']) == 1 
                                                            else ('00'+x['dep_time'] if len(x['dep_time']) == 2
                                                            else x['dep_time']), axis=1)
    df['arr_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: '000'+x['arr_time'] if len(x['arr_time']) == 1 
                                                            else ('00'+x['arr_time'] if len(x['arr_time']) == 2
                                                            else x['arr_time']), axis=1)
    df['sched_dep_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: '000'+x['sched_dep_time'] if len(x['sched_dep_time']) == 1 
                                                            else ('00'+x['sched_dep_time'] if len(x['sched_dep_time']) == 2
                                                            else x['sched_dep_time']), axis=1)
    df['sched_arr_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: '000'+x['sched_arr_time'] if len(x['sched_arr_time']) == 1 
                                                            else ('00'+x['sched_arr_time'] if len(x['sched_arr_time']) == 2
                                                            else x['sched_arr_time']), axis=1)
    
    
    # format time colums to hh:mm:ss
    df['dep_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: x['dep_time'][:-2] + ":" + x['dep_time'][-2:] + ":00", axis=1)
    df['arr_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: x['arr_time'][:-2] + ":" + x['arr_time'][-2:] + ":00", axis=1)
    df['sched_dep_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: x['sched_dep_time'][:-2] + ":" + x['sched_dep_time'][-2:] + ":00", axis=1)
    df['sched_arr_time'] = df.apply(lambda x: x['sched_arr_time'][:-2] + ":" + x['sched_arr_time'][-2:] + ":00", axis=1)
    
    # return 00:00:00 arrival and departure time values to NaN
    df['dep_time'].replace('00:00:00', np.NaN, inplace=True)
    df['arr_time'].replace('00:00:00', np.NaN, inplace=True)

    # display dataframe
    return df

Structure of the data:¶

There are 5,503,507 flight records in the flights_plot dataset with 18 features: ('year', 'month', 'day_of_week', 'carrier_code', 'arr_delay', 'dep_delay', 'distance', 'cancelled', 'reason_for_cancel', 'carrier', 'airport_origin', 'city_origin', 'state_origin', 'airport_dest', 'city_dest', 'state_dest', 'flight_status', 'time_of_day') distributed across quantitative and qualitative datatypes.

Main features of interest:¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are responsible for flight delays and flight cancellations. I am looking to answer the following questions:

  • When is the best time of day/day/week/time of year to fly to minimise delays?
  • What is the top reason for flight cancellations?
  • Are there certain airlines that are home to more delays or cancellations?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that factors such as time of the year, day of the week, time of day, location, carrier(or airline) as well as weather affect the status of a flight (whether it is on time, is delayed or cancelled).

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate distributions of individual variables. These will help me to take a deeper look at the dataset, clean things up in case of any unusual points or outliers, and prepare to look at relationships between variables.

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variables of interest: flight_status and reason_for_cancel:

def insert_pct(df, column, y_plus):
    for i in range(df[column].nunique()):
        count = df[column].value_counts()[i]
        total = df[column].count()
        pct_string = f"{100*count/total:0.2f}%"
        plt.text(i, count+y_plus, pct_string, ha='center', va='center');

def plot_delay_hist(df, column, ax):
    """function to plot distribution of departure and arrival delays"""
    sns.set_style('white')
    bins = np.arange(df[column].min(), df[column].max()+150, 150)
    ax.hist(df[column], bins = bins)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.yticks([10e0, 10e1, 10e2, 10e3, 10e4, 10e5, 10e6, 10e7], [1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000, 100000, 1000000, 10000000]);

Initially the plots showed a single peak between -100 and 100 and other parts of the distribution were barely visible because of large number of counts associated with this range. Applying a log transform to the y axis revealed that the plot was multimodal, having three(3) peaks and most points falling below 15 minutes (which constitutes flights considered on time)

The distribution of arrival and departure delays are almost alike. This should be because a departure delay most likely will result in an arrival delay. It also looks like more planes arrive late than take-off late.

def plot_props(df, column, ylabel):
    """function to plot percentage delay per city"""
    pct_props = []
    col_values = df[column].unique()
    top_10_counts = df[column].value_counts().index[:10]
    for value in col_values:
        pct_prop = 100 * (df[column].value_counts()[value] / flights_plot[column].value_counts()[value])
        pct_props.append(pct_prop) 
    prop_dict = {column:col_values, 'pct_delay':pct_props}
    the_df = pd.DataFrame(prop_dict).set_index(column).sort_values(by='pct_delay', ascending=False)
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    the_df.loc[top_10_counts].plot(kind='bar', legend=False)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

def plot_avg_delay(column):
    """
    function to plot average delay.
    
    input: column to plot by
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, sharex=True, figsize=(6, 6))

    delay_sub.groupby(column)['dep_delay'].mean().plot(ax=ax[0], ylim=(0, 40))
    delay_sub.groupby(column)['arr_delay'].mean().plot(ax=ax[1], ylim=(-5, 30))
    ax[0].set_ylabel('mean departure delay')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('mean arrival delay')

    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

I set out to answer the following questions in my analysis:

  • When is the best time of day/day/week/time of year to fly to minimise delays?
  • What is the top reason for flight cancellations?
  • Are there certain airlines that are home to more delays or cancellations?

Having performed univariate, bivariate and multivariate exploration of the data, I have the following conclusions:

  • Early morning flights are the least delayed and late night flights are the least cancelled.
  • The top reason for flight cancellation is the carrier.
  • Atlantic Southeast Airlines has the most delays. Mesa Airlines followed by Atlantic Southeast Airlines has the most cancellations. Atlantic Southeast Airlines is associated with lots of delays and cancellations.
  • Atlanta is home to more delays.
